    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "it's just humming and nothing else. i was thinking maybe it's the capacitor? i've heard people say they go bad and cause that exact sound. how can i tell if a capacitor is actually dead or if it's something else? also i'm pretty careful about power, so what should i look out for if i do pop the cover off?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A humming noise can be caused by a dead capacitor, but it's also possible that it's an air leak or a blockage in the refrigerant line. To determine if the issue is with a capacitor, look for signs of physical damage or the capacitor's likely location, such as near the compressor or blower motor.\n\nWhen inspecting the capacitor, check if it's holding voltage (even when the unit is off) and if it's marked with the correct voltage rating. Also, it's essential to follow proper safety precautions, such as setting your circuit breaker or switching the unit off at the circuit breaker, before opening the cover.",
